you know what else is crazy?     alphabet, set of graphs, or characters, used to represent the phonemic structure of a language. In most alphabets the characters are arranged in a definite order, or sequence (e.g., A, B, C, etc.).  In the usual case, each alphabetic character represents either a consonant or a vowel rather than a syllable or a group of consonants and vowels. As a result, the number of characters required can be held to a relative few. A language that has 30 consonant sounds and five vowels, for example, needs at most only 35 separate letters. In a syllabary, on the other hand, the same language would require 30 Ã— 5 symbols to represent each possible consonant-vowel syllable (e.g., separate forms for ba, be, bi, bo, bu; da, de, di; and so on) and an additional five symbols for the vowels, thereby making a total of 155 individual characters. Both syllabaries and alphabets are phonographic symbolizations; that is, they represent the sounds of words rather than units of meaning.  The word alphabet, from the first two letters of the Greek alphabetâ€”alpha and betaâ€”was first used, in its Latin form, alphabetum, by Tertullian (2ndâ€“3rd century CE), a Latin ecclesiastical writer and Church Father, and by St. Jerome. The Classical Greeks customarily used the plural of to gramma (â€œthe letterâ€); the later form alphabÄ“tos was probably adopted under Latin influence.  The evolution of the alphabet involved two important achievements. The first was the step taken by a group of Semitic-speaking people, perhaps the Phoenicians, on the eastern shore of the Mediterranean between 1700 and 1500 BCE. This was the invention of a consonantal writing system known as North Semitic. The second was the invention, by the Greeks, of characters for representing vowels. This step occurred between 800 and 700 BCE. While some scholars consider the Semitic writing system an unvocalized syllabary and the Greek system the true alphabet, both are treated here as forms of the alphabet.   Over the centuries, various theories have been advanced to explain the origin of alphabetic writing, and, since Classical times, the problem has been a matter of serious study. The Greeks and Romans considered five different peoples as the possible inventors of the alphabetâ€”the Phoenicians, Egyptians, Assyrians, Cretans, and Hebrews. Among modern theories are some that are not very different from those of ancient days. Every country situated in or more or less near the eastern Mediterranean has been singled out for the honour. Egyptian writing, cuneiform, Cretan, hieroglyphic Hittite, the Cypriot syllabary, and other scripts have all been called prototypes of the alphabet. The Egyptian theory actually subdivides into three separate theories, according to whether the Egyptian hieroglyphic, the hieratic, or the demotic script is regarded as the true parent of alphabetic writing. Similarly, the idea that cuneiform was the precursor of the alphabet may also be subdivided into those singling out Sumerian, Babylonian, or Assyrian cuneiform.  Among the various other theories concerning the alphabet are the hypotheses that the alphabet was taken by the Philistines from Crete to Palestine, that the various ancient scripts of the Mediterranean countries developed from prehistoric geometric symbols employed throughout the Mediterranean area from the earliest times, and that the proto-Sinaitic inscriptions (discovered since 1905 in the Sinai Peninsula) represent a stage of writing intermediate between the Egyptian hieroglyphics and the North Semitic alphabet. Another hypothesis, the Ugaritic theory, evolved after an epoch-making discovery in 1929 (and the years following) at the site of the ancient Ugarit, on the Syrian coast opposite the most easterly cape of Cyprus. Thousands of clay tablets were found there, documents of inestimable value in many fields of research (including epigraphy, philology, and the history of religion). Dating from the 15th and 14th centuries BCE, they were written in a cuneiform alphabet of 30 letters.

Fn is a simple way of abbreviating "fine." It's most often used to say "that's fine," in response to a statement or question. For example, if your SO asks whether you're okay with having Chinese food for dinner, and Chinese is okay by you, you could answer with a simple "yup, tht's fn."

Period: Freeze a letter. Comma: Slow a letter. Semicolon and Colon: Conjoin a letter. Exclamation Mark: Speeds up a letter. Asterisk: Multiply a letter. Here's what I think will happen (Mike, you don't need to make another sequel, I don't want to see F die again)  Since now N and F got eachother's back, F has no reason to turn evil and, when they grow up again to uppercase, they will try to reconcile all the letters together, just like F was trying to do before but in more peaceful ways. Maybe F will be remembered as "the one who formed a swear word" but since now N has the question mark, he will remind them that it was accidental (because it was L and O that pushed F) and everyone will frown at L and O because they were bullies. At this point, there are three options:  1- L and O apologize for what they have done in the past and everyone live happily ever after (the ending everyone would want)  2- L and O will feel attacked so they'll separate from everyone and turn evil (then other battles take place which would probably lead at least 1 letter to death)  3- Everyone starts attacking L and O, which will lead to option 2 (this is the most likely to happen, imo)  However, no matter what happens, N  now can predict the future instead of Q. and, since Z certainly wouldn't want to intervene twice and rewind time once again (also letters wouldn't want to live their lowercasehood thrice) he now can pretty much stop things from happening because he has learned not to be a coward, which made him have F's back.   But what if Z had to intervene another time? I mean, still, N would warn everyone but what if his warnings failed like Q's did? Depending on which between options 2 and 3 took place, Z would probably act like a god and either scold L and O for causing all potential rivalries (and then remind them they were the reason F turned evil in the past) or the others for the "cycle of revenge" thing.   I can already see someone saying "maybe F and N will turn evil and history will kind of repeat itself". I don't think that would happen for two reasons:  1- It's true, N is no longer a coward but he still has a heart and definitely needs support, if he turned evil he wouldn't stand a chance against the letters who have the punctuation powers. Remember, F and N still cried the full stop, comma, colon and exclamation mark, which can still be used by L, M, O and P. Arguably, having the question mark does make N one of the most powerful letters but only emotionally, besides predicting the future what else can you really do?  2- if F started leaning back towards evil, N would stop him right away, either by using the question mark or by reminding F he was the one who gave him moral support after L and O hit him.  I hope someone sees this, since holy shit 25000 comments already, this better not get lost

My guess as to what's happened here is that Z managed to get his Punctuation Gem through careful recreation of the Period Gem. This made it much more powerful than the normal Punctuation Gems, rewriting history. However, the Punctuation Gems were created by F, including the Question Mark Gem. This is basically F asking N "Why?" So, N receiving the  Question Mark Gem is N realizing what he had done wrong. With this happening at the same time as Z's Artificial Punctuation Gem rewriting time, causes the rewriting of history to be influenced. This sort of carries over N's realization into lowercase N, causing him to reject L, M, and O, and ally with F. This is my interpretation of what this Epilogue means.

The ellipsis... (/ÉªËˆlÉªpsÉªs/, also known informally as dot dot dot) is a series of dots that indicates an intentional omission of a word, sentence, or whole section from a text without altering its original meaning. The plural is ellipses. The term originates from the Ancient Greek: á¼”Î»Î»ÎµÎ¹ÏˆÎ¹Ï‚, Ã©lleipsis meaning 'leave out'.

Since this episode was pretty hard to comprehend, I'll break it down for those confused.            The episode starts after the plot of Z, right after F's death. However, Z is uncontented with this as everyone is sad, and uses the power of the ellipsis (which he cried out when F was rejected by the community, just before the plot of A) by spinning them counter-clockwise around him.           Z goes all the way back to the flashback N had, where everyone is younger. f then trips over n, but this time n remembers the future. He looks at the letters "protecting" him, he remembers how O hurt him, he remembers how L bullied him, but then he looked at f. F never wronged him, they were broken buddies through-and-through. He looks at the ground, remembers everyone else and how they wronged him.           n, with this knowledge, decides to overpower the guilt from the other letters he felt before, and instead helps f. f is happy about this, but l and o aren't. They attack f and n, but they're happy. f and n cry out the rest of the punctuations, in a joyful, thankful way. n hugs p because p never wronged him. f and n go to F's castle, which makes the letters who rejected f and n happy. This way, every letter is content and happy in one way or another, thus making z content.  Also, in the description, Mike says that the "Epilogue" will be the final four episodes, so there is 3 episodes left. The last 3 episodes will probably do the entire ending part of the ABCs song for the names, so I believe the Epilogue episodes will be called "Now I Know My ABCs," "Next Time," "Won't You," and "Sing With Me." These episodes will probably go through the new plot of this rewound universe.
